05684nam a22006735i 9781501750762DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017507627 a10.1515/97815017507622doi  a(DE-B1597)551300  a(OCoLC)1126359804  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0370702bisacsh04a261.8/7088282732231 aKeeley, Theresa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReagan's Gun-Toting Nuns :bThe Catholic Conflict over Cold War Human Rights Policy in Central America /cTheresa Keeley. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2020] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b4 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Catholic Divisions, U.S.–Central America Policy, and the Cold War -- t1. From Senator McCarthy’s Darlings to Marxist Maryknollers -- t2. Religious or Political Activists for Nicaragua? -- t3. Subversives in El Salvador -- t4. U.S. Guns Kill U.S. Nuns -- t5. Reagan and the White House’s Maryknoll Nun -- t6. Real Catholics versus Maryknollers -- t7. Maryknoll and Iran-Contra -- t8. Déjà Vu: Jesuits and Maryknollers -- tEpilogue: Women, the Catholic Church, and U.S.–Central America Relations after the Cold War -- tNotes on Research Methods -- tNotes -- tPrimary Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Reagan's Gun-Toting Nuns, Theresa Keeley analyzes the role of intra-Catholic conflict within the framework of U.S. foreign policy formulation and execution during the Reagan administration. She challenges the preponderance of scholarship on the administration that stresses the influence of evangelical Protestants on foreign policy toward Latin America. Especially in the case of U.S. engagement in El Salvador and Nicaragua, Keeley argues, the bitter debate between U.S. and Central American Catholics over the direction of the Catholic Church shaped President Reagan's foreign policy. The flash point for these intra-Catholic disputes was the December 1980 political murder of four American Catholic missionaries in El Salvador. Liberal Catholics described nuns and priests in Central America who worked to combat structural inequality as human rights advocates living out the Gospel's spirit. Conservative Catholics saw them as agents of class conflict who furthered the so-called Gospel according to Karl Marx. The debate was an old one among Catholics, but, as Reagan's Gun-Toting Nuns contends, it intensified as conservative, anticommunist Catholics played instrumental roles in crafting U.S. policy to fund the Salvadoran government and the Nicaraguan Contras.Reagan's Gun-Toting Nuns describes the religious actors as human rights advocates and, against prevailing understandings of the fundamentally secular activism related to human rights, highlights religion-inspired activism during the Cold War. In charting the rightward development of American Catholicism, Keeley provides a new chapter in the history of U.S. diplomacy and shows how domestic issues such as contraception and abortion joined with foreign policy matters to shift Catholic laity toward Republican principles at home and abroad.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCatholic Church and world politicsxHistoryy20th century. 0aCatholicsxPolitical activityzCentral AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 0aCatholicsxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aChristianity and international relationsxHistoryy20th century. 0aReligion and politicszUnited States. 4aLatin History. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aLiberation Theology, Cold War, Maryknoll, Catholic History, Central America.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501750762?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501750762423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501750762/original  a978-3-11-069046-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070473-0  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishb2020  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2020  aZDB-23-DGGb2020